#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""
Bush Glue TTS bench harness.

Drives each TTS engine adapter against a corpus of input texts and emits a CSV
with TTFA + RTF + latency + CPU + RAM per (text, engine, run). This is the
sibling artifact to bush-stt-bench: it's how we pick the TTS engine per
eng review §6.

Usage:
    bush-tts-bench --corpus <file_or_dir> --engine <name>[,<name>...] \\
        --output <csv> [--repeat N] [--warmup N] [--voice <path>] [--mos]

The --corpus argument is either:
    - a TSV file with columns: <text_id>\\t<text>\\t<category>
    - a directory containing a texts.tsv file with the same format

A ready-to-use corpus ships at data/tts-bench-corpus.tsv.

Engines are loaded lazily; an engine that cannot be imported (module missing,
construction failure, missing voice file, etc.) is skipped with a warning so
the bench remains robust as new engines arrive.

When --mos is passed, after each synthesis the bench writes a temp WAV and
prompts the operator to rate the audio 1-5 (mean opinion score) or 's' to skip.

Required Python deps (NOT in pyproject — bench is a dev tool):
    pip install psutil>=5.9   # CPU + RAM monitoring
    # soxr only if a future engine resamples; current engines (espeak, piper)
    # don't need it because we never decode the audio for analysis.

If psutil is missing the bench keeps running with sentinel -1 values
in the CPU/RAM columns and prints a one-line install hint.
"""
import os
import sys

